{
  "text": "The 18 saplings were kept in the greenhouse during the 3 weeks of incubation, and half of them (6 labeled and 3 unlabeled) were randomly selected and submitted to two cycles of drought (11 and 10 days) by withholding irrigation (Fig. 1) . Every second day, predawn needle water potential (Ψ wp ) was measured with a Scholander pressure chamber, and gas exchange of a current year twig with a 4L portable photosynthesis chamber LiCor 6 200 (LiCor, Lincoln, Nebraska, USA), around midday (between 12 h 30 and 14 h 00 local Figure 1 . Flow diagram presenting the schedule of the experiment, with three periods of [CITATION_1] C labeling followed by an inoculation with Ophiostoma brunneo-ciliatum, two successive drought cycles, and sampling of the Scot pine saplings at the end of the experiment. time). Net CO 2 assimilation rate (A, μmol m −2 s −1 ) and stomatal conductance to water vapor (g s , μmol m −2 s −1 ) were computed as in [CITATION_2] . At the end of the experiment, saplings were harvested and the projected needle area was measured with a leaf area meter (Delta-T Devices, Cambridge, UK). Once Ψ wp had reached a threshold of around -2 MPa (after approx. 10 days), saplings were watered to field capacity and left to dehydrate freely again for a second drought cycle. Saplings were sampled at the end of this second cycle.",
